        <Parent_String>dulcimers [300042163], zitherlike chordophones: struck [300209226], zitherlike chordophones [300224193], chordophones [300041641], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Dulcimers of Turkey, Iraq, Iran, the Caucasus, southeastern Europe, and South Asia, varying regionally but generally consisting of a trapezoidal hardwood box with the metal or nylon strings arranged in courses of three, four, or even five, passing over individual bridges and attached to the side of the box by tuning pegs. They are struck with two sticks.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Dulcimers de Turquía, Irak, Irán, el Cáucaso, el sudeste de Europa, y Asia del Sur, diferentes según las regiones pero que generalmente consisten en una caja de madera dura trapezoidal con cuerdas de metal o nailon organizadas en órdenes de tres, cuatro o eventualmente cinco cuerdas, que pasan sobre puentes individuales y están sujetas al costado de la caja mediante clavijas de afinación. Se golpean con dos palillos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hakkeborden, in allerlei per streek verschillende uitvoeringen, trapeziumvormige hardhouten klankkast, snaren van metaal of nylon, in koren van 3, 4 of 5 over individuele kammen lopend, stemschroeven aan beide zijden van de kast; bespeeld met 2 stokjes; Turkije, Irak, Iran, Kaukasus, Zuidoost-Europa, Zuid-Azië.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指土耳其、伊拉克、伊朗、高加索地區、東南歐、南亞的揚琴，形式因地而異，不過通常具有硬木製的梯形共鳴箱，以及三至五組金屬弦或尼龍弦，琴弦橫過個別的琴橋，固定於共鳴箱側邊的調音弦鈕，以兩根棒子敲擊演奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hackbrett aus der Türkei, dem Irak, Iran, Kaukasus, Südosteuropa und Südasien, regional unterschiedlich, aber allgemein bestehend aus einem trapezförmigen Resonanzkasten aus Hartholz mit Metall- oder Nylonsaiten in Chören zu drei, vier oder sogar fünf Saiten angeordnet, die über einzelne Stege laufen und an der Seite des Kastens durch Stimmwirbel befestigt sind. Das Instrument wird mit zwei Klöppeln angeschlagen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
